The paper deals with a problem in information theory (index coding) and uses linear programming and duality techniques to provide bounds on the minimum number of transmissions required for any coding algorithm. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the cs.IT (Information Theory) sub-category. Additionally, the paper deals with the transmission of packets to multiple receivers, which suggests that it may also belong to the cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) sub-category. The paper also mentions the use of bipartite digraphs, which suggests that it may belong to the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) sub-category. The paper also deals with the relationship between index coding, duality, and integrality gaps, which suggests that it may belong to the cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) sub-category. Finally, the paper uses linear programming and integer programming techniques, which suggests that it may also belong to the cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-category.
